<section class="card">
  <h2>What Is a “Last Frost Date”?</h2>

  <p>
    Your <strong>average last frost date</strong> is the typical final spring freeze in your area.
    It’s calculated from historical weather data and represents the date when frost is unlikely — not impossible.
  </p>

  <p>
    A few important clarifications:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>It’s based on past averages, not a prediction for this year.</li>
    <li>Some years will have a later freeze.</li>
    <li>Microclimates can shift real-world conditions slightly.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Think of it as a planning anchor — not a guarantee.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Look Up Your Average Last Frost Date</h2>

  <p>
    You can find your frost date using:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>National weather databases</li>
    <li>Local extension office websites</li>
    <li>Reliable frost date calculators online</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Enter your ZIP code or nearest city, and you’ll see an estimated average last frost date.
  </p>

  <p>
    Write that date down — you’ll use it repeatedly throughout the season.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>USDA Zones vs. Frost Dates</h2>

  <p>
    USDA hardiness zones describe average winter minimum temperatures.
    They do <strong>not</strong> tell you your exact last frost date.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two gardeners in the same zone can have different frost timing.
    Always check your specific location rather than relying on zone alone.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How Accurate Is the Average?</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates are usually presented at probability levels — for example, a 30% chance of frost after that date.
  </p>

  <p>
    This means:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Most years, frost will be finished by that date.</li>
    <li>Some years, a late frost can still occur.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If you’re risk-averse, you can add a small buffer of 5–7 days.
    If you use protection (like row cover), you may be comfortable planting slightly earlier.
  </p>
</section>

