<section class="card">
  <h2>Short Growing Seasons: A Practical Note</h2>

  <p>
    In colder climates, your frost date often arrives later in spring.
    That shortens the growing window — but it doesn’t automatically mean starting seeds much earlier indoors.
  </p>

  <p>
    The transplant date drives success.
    The indoor start date supports it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Using your actual frost date — instead of guessing — prevents leggy seedlings and timing stress.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>What if I can’t find an exact frost date for my town?</summary>
    <p>
      Use the nearest city with reliable weather data. Small differences are normal, and you can add a small buffer if needed.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Can I plant before my last frost date?</summary>
    <p>
      Cold-tolerant crops often can. Warm-season crops like tomatoes and peppers should wait until after frost risk has passed.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Is my frost date the same every year?</summary>
    <p>
      No. It varies slightly each year. That’s why it’s listed as an average.
    </p>
  </details>
</section>

